 is maybe a typographical error

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:58.240
 that you've seen in an error message.

00:08:58.240 --> 00:08:59.800
 So that's the shell interface.

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:01.320
 And again, part of what I wanna show you

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.320
 is for you to know when you're talking to the shell,

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.080
 'cause you're not always talking to the shell.

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:07.640
 If it ends in a dollar sign prompt,

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:09.120
 usually you're talking to the shell.

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:10.960
 So let's take a look at what it might look like

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:13.240
 in different situations.

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:16.080
 So sometimes you just run Python interactively.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:17.440
 And if you've taken a Python course,

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:21.560
 this is the REPL, the read, evaluate something loop.

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:24.560
 So you just type Python

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:26.160
 and it's running Python interactively.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:29.040
 Now you're still sitting in a prompt, okay?

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:32.340
 And so now that's not the same thing.

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:33.800
 That's not Linux talking to you,

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:35.200
 that's Python talking to you.

00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:37.240
 You're running the command Python on Linux

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:39.740
 and that Python command is asking for input.

00:09:39.740 --> 00:09:41.940
 So it expects you to type Python.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:45.560
 Hello world, of course we're gonna type hello world.

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.860
 And that reads the Python, parses it, and then executes it.

00:09:49.860 --> 00:09:52.160
 Now, if you're in this and you type LS,

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:53.480
 it's like, I don't know what to do.

00:09:53.480 --> 00:09:54.640
 I have no idea.

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:56.840
 PWD, I have no idea what you're doing

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:58.440
 'cause you're not in the shell.

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:00.040
 So students come to me and go like,

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:03.080
 I keep typing PWD and it's giving me name errors.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:04.880
 Like, well, that's 'cause you're in Python,

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:06.080
 not in the shell.

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:08.440
 So you have to know how to exit.

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:11.760
 And you do that with quit, open paren, close paren, enter.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.140
 And now you're back to the happy little dollar sign prompt.

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:17.980
 And now you can say PWD and it will work, right?

00:10:17.980 --> 00:10:21.960
 So part of it is recognizing what you're interacting with

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:24.720
 based on what the prompt looks like, okay?

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:26.800
 So that's the Python interface.

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:31.800
 Now, if you end up with a more than one line Python statement

00:10:32.680 --> 00:10:36.200
 that the three chevrons prompts turns into a dot, dot, dot.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:37.520
 Let me show you how that works.

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:38.960
 So I'm gonna run Python again.

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:41.680
 I'm just cursoring up Python.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:46.680
 And I can say, for i in range five, colon.

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:50.760
 Now you see that the prompt is turned into a dot, dot, dot.

00:10:50.760 --> 00:10:52.260
 And I have to do an indent, of course.

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:55.400
 One, two, three, four, five, print i.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:59.240
 And it's still thinking that I'm in this for loop.

00:10:59.240 --> 00:11:01.040
 And so it's saying, are you still doing more stuff

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:01.860
 in the for loop?

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:03.240
 I could put another line in this for loop.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:07.420
 I could say, print second line.

00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:11.480
 And then I can hit the enter and say,

00:11:11.480 --> 00:11:12.720
 I'm done with the for loop.

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:15.080
 And then we'll actually read the for loop,

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:17.280
 run the for loop, execute it five times

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:19.440
 with i being zero, one, two, three, four.

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.560
 But the body loop has two things.

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:24.040
 And then when it's done with this sort of continuation,

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:27.080
 dot, dot, dot is like, I need more, I'm not done yet.

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:29.400
 Whatever you typed, it's not finished.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:31.960
 Now I'm back to the standard Chevron prompt,

00:11:31.960 --> 00:11:33.700
 at which case I would type quit.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:36.760
 And now I'm back to the shell prompt.

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:38.760
 See, the whole idea is to be able to record,

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:41.320
 it's like, don't get lost because it's asking,

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:42.980
 you're talking to the wrong thing.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:46.360
 Okay, so that's one thing.

